Lucy 
May 13 1835                                                                                                                                        Bangor May 13 1835
Dear Lucy
I have been naughty not to write to  you before, since Isaac & Stella came, but I know Isaac wrote last week, so I thought you would not care so much.  It seems so odd to have them at Eliah's instead of here, but we have seen them about every day so far.  What a splendid specimen of health and manliness little Bray is! I wish I could ((unclear)) not to be such a clinger to "Mamma".  He is never really happy but a few moments at a time, even out doors, unless "Mamma" will  "drop floor" with him and keep by his side. To get down anywhere at any time, on the floor in the house, or on the ground, is "drop floor."  It seems as if he could not be weaned from me.  When out doors with Lizzie
Completed

and May's, if I am not there too, he must come in every few minutes and stand & look at me a little & then out again.  If I am out of sight a moment, when he is ever so lazy at play, it is "Mamma away," Mamma away, away away".  Liz's being here will be a capital thing for her.  I taken him over to her care a good deal & he is learning to love her very much.
15- When I had got so far.  I saw Nellie & Mays came, Nellie says she wrote a long letter to you when she said everything, so that I need not write at present, but as I had begun, thought I might as well finish - I have not been very well for a little past  - distress through my chest, right side, back & shoulder blade - much ((unclear)) and by swallowing.  Sabbath it grew more painful & Dr Nic came in the evening - said he had
Completed

many such cases this spring. Slight inflammation of pleura and lungs. I felt sabbath day exactly as when sick at Hampden.  He left me medicine, recommended hot foot baths, mustard poultice on the side & ((unclear)) powder the second day.  I feel almost well today-think some of going shopping & taking my physic after I come back.  Lizzie is out on the sidewalk with ((unclear)).  I am going to see about a bonnet for Almeda & getting Lizzie's fixed over.  ((unclear)) has had a fresh installment of ((unclear)) from Easthampton?? as many more minerals , ((unclear)) in a & justly things as she had before.  Netties says - I have not seen ((unclear)) - Her bonnet & Gertie's hat are coming from N.York City-Hatties has got also a coral necklace ( & amulets to match) with a gold clasp & little locket, marked "G.E.M." for Gertie.  We think such arrangements are
Completed

wasted powder, but please don't say anything when you write.  It will do no good, only trouble the feelings.  I am anxious to hear if the rose arrived safely and is likely to live, if not there are plenty more here, if I can ever get a chance to send them.
P.M Nettie, Mallie & self went shopping as proposed -  accomplished a fine parcel of business - spoke for Almedas bonnet.  Nettie is up here this afternoon.  ((unclear)) setting out currant bushes, Mays & ((unclear)) running about in the yard.  Lizzie gone up to the grove with Lizzie Page, Ellen down town.  I thank you much for the root - am using it faithfully - in much haste with great care.
AM caught today Mr Beascroft died a few days time, little less than a year since his wife died - I will try to send you an obituary
Completed

*any special requests as apologies through to Mr ((unclear)) people, to Alice because what I gave her for a lily was only a lilac.  I thought lilys were lilacs while all the while they were not out of the ground.  don't feel too much harm were done, know she'll think strange in haste.  Good hope & good night.

Lovingly 
Lucy                                                                                                                                                



May 22nd 55

                                                                                                                                                 Bangor - May 22nd 1855


Dear Mother
I am afraid you think I have been rather remiss about writing lately, but there has not seemed to be anything to write.  Isaac and I have been gardening more or less every day - By his kind assistance, my posey garden thrives wonderfully.  I like ever so much comfort working out there & I believe grow strong daily.  Percie is out as much as half the time when it is pleasant, -  his chucks are growing delightfully hard and rosey as well as his skin getting to look fine brown - he tans really easy.  He is talking to Lizzie finally, though nobody is quite equal to Mamma yet. Lizzie is more womanly than when here before, & of course two years ought to make some diff
Completed

((unclear)) Mays has been really sick with cold and cankered mouth (as ((unclear)) was last winter only worse for about a week, it is getting better now.  Gertie is a little mite of a thing - only think - nine months old in a day or two,  wears long white dresses, & does not begin to sit alone yet.  She seems smart to jump & fly around in ones lap, but she has great old ((unclear)) of organisation - so very narrow across the shoulders.  Maria is not very ((unclear)), had a great many ((unclear)) feelings.  This she keeps sound, & wouldn't like to have me say she was not well as anybody, so you must not say anything when you write.  She don't like to have anything said because I tell her I know her present feelings are owing to ((unclear)) best face.  She and Nellie have gone.  I suppose, to
Completed

hear Mrs Johnson  lecture to ladies on health this afternoon - this is her second course of seven lectures, said to be worth everybody's hearing.  We have got a beautiful silk bonnet making for Almeda.  I have covered the lounge self alone today I am slightly weary.  Am very much better than when you went away.  After you went away I devoted myself to doing nothing, only to read or write when I felt like it & occasionally to do a little work, for two or three weeks.  Whether this benefitted me or whether being out doors a good deal, or taking  considerable currant wine, or the or the miracle of the root you sent, I know not - perhaps all combined.  By the way, please remind I must prepare &  ((unclear)) the root while green without fail, so I fixed all of it - equal to some hundred dozen whites
Completed

of eggs!  Just a quart of wine with it to keep it, and laboured daily upon it with extreme diligence, (so thick it formed like whites of eggs, and consequently not particularly agreeable,) but some of it spoiled before I could use it all - if I had dried the root & used it as I wanted it, it would have been better.  Letters from Minnesota yesterday bring tidings of an infant daughter born to Bill Watson the 9 - of May.  Theodore has 100 acres under plough this spring.  You ask what preparation you can make to go to Elysia - I don't see as anything but to stand ready, at least till you got as far as here.  We want you here  these days badly - As for all of us coming to Milo together; I don't think it best to crush, overwhelm & ((unclearly)) you all at once.  We have got a new "Prairie rose", honeysuckle (only not a very handsome kind) Lily of the Valley this spring, besides new fruit & forest trees, I wish you would please
Completed

Lucy  May 1833
Dear Mother
As Nettie says  "I fully intended", and have done so almost every mail since they came from Milo, yet I believe you have not had so many letters as usual from me - When there are so many of us here, there is more going on- particularly shopping, particularly now, Nettie had a good  many things to get, & our spring fixing, though we have not done much at fixing this year.  I am very well for me & growing "weller".  Samuel has not been quite well for a few days - I feel almost as if Isaac ought not to go west without you going to Elysia, yet I am afraid to have you go to stay through the hot weather.  The Dr) & Anna seem determind not to give in use but that I am going.  But I cannot feel
Not Started

that it would be quite right this year on account of expenses besides Samuel wants to go as much as I  to ((unclear)) too, and I think I had better wait & go with him.  Then if he should be sick and I ((unclear.))
I am sorry - because in regard to  orders, health & everything, I am well ((unclear)) to go this year.  In regard to yourself, I do not know what is best, I am sure - it is for you to decide whether to go immediately with Isaac or wait and go in the fall - he will be going then I suppose.  The fish matter will be specially attended to, I cannot contribute any way for us all to go to Milo together without making much  additional expense, as I dare not go by stage, besides the fatiguing considerations for you & ((unclear)) with us may perplex babies Eliah & Marcia how better go cosily together in a chaise when they get ready, if we can, the last of Summer, Samuel & I will go.  In haste with much love to all.
Lucy
Completed

Lucy Furber June 23 1835                                                                                                   Bangor June 23rd 1835
Dear Mother
I imagine you will feel somewhat anxious before Monday night to hear of our welfare, but there seems to be no way of sending before that time.  Eliah will write Monday, I presume, and tell you what a comfortable ride we had had home - I never was on the road what it was so bad, - partly in consequence of heavy ((unclear)) passing since the rain, and partly because of refraining when the ground was so wet.  We got here safe, but very tired.  Perrie seemed to think that already but ((unclear)), not even his father could do anything for him, but he soon got over it, for I was obliged to go to bed.  He seemed delighted to get home, and after a little time went to play with Lizzie and was very good all the afternoon.  He seemed quite "runctious" when he first wakened, but feels needy now - do write much & often.
Lucy
Will put in the silk now & send the braid with the bundle soon.
Completed

weak and does this morning - tips over easily.  Was rather restless last night, started in his sleep often, but I laid it to getting too tired.  He has been out in the piazza this morning and is playing about as usual.  I feel well this morning, what the exception of being sleepy, tired, lame, and back achy!  Was it not fortunate that we had the ((unclear)) instead of the afternoon to come home in?  We found a letter here for Nellie - wanted to read it, but thought she might like to also finish.  Only Mrs Harlow, Mrs; Martin & Mrs blood have been in this morning - all on errands.  There are fifteen fully blown peonies under the winder.  The ((unclear)) were in fine order when they got here.  Our visit at Milo does not seem to be very satisfactory to look back upon.  Fatigue, anxiety & sickness on our part, and loss of sleep,((unclear))
Completed

((unclear)) and anxiety for all of you.  I am sad to think of you Mother, with your cold from Perrie is keeping you inconvened, & then so tired and without sleep all night.  I hope you all went to heal after we came away - particularly Mother and ((unclear)).  Perrie had no trouble with his diarhorrea on the way down, and so little now, that unless it increases, I shall not think best to check it.  I feel nicely to think we are likely to get along without a doctor.  We will see to the things and try to send them up the fist of the week - I got a letter from Samuel on the way home - the driver had it in his hat & thought best not to keep me waiting!  Ellen & Lizzie were pretty glad to see us - If jam cannot be obtained there, had I better send any.  Please ask Almeda if she would like a further jar sent?
